rKornwachs, Klaus -- tPart III: Per/versions of Cultural Diversity: Including Exclusions -- tGlobal Pressures and Cultural Relativity: The Case of Media Anthropology / rPfeiffer, K. Ludwig -- tLong-Term Power Presentation Shifts: From Key Audio-Visual Narratives to an Update of Elias's Theory on the Process of Civilization / rLudes, Peter -- tInner Language Spaces: Migration and Plurilingualism from a Psycholinguistic Perspective / rLindorfer, Bettina -- tRelational Diversity: Religious Pluralization and Politics of Cohesion / rNagel, Alexander-Kenneth -- tManifesting Religion in Public: A Universal Human Right - An International Law - National Restrictions / rKippenberg, Hans G. -- tPart IV: Peroration -- tDevolvement: From Modern Humanities towards Global Humanities / rMersmann, Birgit / Kippenberg, Hans G. -- tList of Illustrations -- tAbout the Authors -- tIndex -- tBackmatter  aModernization and digital globalization have proven to mark major thresholds where paradigmatic shifts and realignments take place. This volume aims to capture the reconfiguration of humanistic study between the forces of global integration and cultural diversification from a full range of disciplines within the humanities and social sciences. The key issue is discussed in three major parts. The first chapter examines transnational interpolations of the humanities as potential indicator for a globalizing humanistic research. The second chapter deals with humanistic revisions of modernity with and against globality. The third chapter discusses the ambiguous constitution of cultural diversity as a complement and counter-movement to global integration, ideologically moving between social cohesion and exclusion. The final chapter outlines what the threshold-crossing from modern to global humanities will mean for the future of humanistic research.The multidisciplinary study of culture within the history of the humanities documents and reflects the mobility and migration of its concepts and methods, moving and translating between disciplines, research traditions, historical periods, academic institutions, and the public sphere.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 16. Mai 2019) 0aCultural pluralismxHistory. 0aGlobalizationxSocial aspectsxHistory. 0aHumanitiesxHistoryy20th century. 0aHumanitiesxHistoryy21st century. 0aHumanitiesxSocial aspectsxHistory. 0aTransnationalismxHistory. 4aCultural Diversity. 4aGlobal Integration. 4aHumanities. 4aTransnational Cultural Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aGurrey, Owen.1 aKippenberg, Hans G., eeditor.1 aMersmann, Birgit, eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2016z9783110485264oZDB-23-DKU0 cEPUBz97831104511150 cprintz978311044075140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110452181423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110452181.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aZDB-23-DGGb2016  aZDB-23-DKUb2016